The schematism of signs signiliter (ζωδιακῶς) regarded the sign as a unit, as itselfa point 3 the line passed from sign to sign. This was the popular and ‘ unscientific ' method (ζωδισκὴ καὶ κοινὴ καὶ καθολικὴ, καθ’ ἣν πάντες πλανώμεθα, ‘Demophilus'). The exacter method was a schematism partiliter (μοιρικῶς), in which the line passed from a given degree (pars, sors, μοῖρα) in one sign to the corresponding degree in the other. For a third method‚ aiming at real exactitude, the mensura χρονικῶς, introduced by Antigonus of Nicaea, see Bouche- Leclercq, pp. 178—9.
